foot
Homonym Number:  1
Word Class: noun
Sense Number:
Definition:a block of wood attached by wire to a post and buried with the post in the posthole; or some other device to stop the post being pulled out when the fence is strained


Origin:
Register:
Register 2:
Domain: [none]
Region: [none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes:
Citations
Date:  0/0/1951
Source:  Letter
Author:  R. GILBERD
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote:  Northland Posts in a dip are called `foot-posts' because they require `footing' to prevent their lifting as wires are strained. A `foot' is a buried block of wood fastened either to the post or to the wires.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1962
Source:  Country Occasions
Author:  SHARPE
Vol / Page:  157
Edition:
Quote:  In the gullies you have to attach a `foot' to a post - a piece of timber or rock firmly slotted and wired into the bottom end.
Notes:

Date:  21/3/1981
Source:  Listener (New Zealand Listener)
Author:
Vol / Page:  67
Edition:
Quote:  Ross prepared a `foot' to wedge into the base of the post. This was done with his well-used rammer. The `foot' was a solid piece of totara with a length of No8 wire stapled to it.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1982
Source:  MAF Agricultural Glossary
